  "End-Permian extinction, known as 'The Great Dying'": "",
  "Late Devonian extinction": "",
  "End-Cretaceous extinction": "",
  "The end-Permian extinction approximately 252 million years ago wiped out roughly 96% of all marine species and 70% of land species, making it by far the most devastating mass extinction event in Earth's history.": "",
  "The end-Cretaceous mass extinction that killed the dinosaurs was caused by:": "",
  "Climate change from human activity": "",
  "A nearby supernova explosion": "",
  "An asteroid impact combined with volcanic activity": "",
  "Only volcanic eruptions": "",
  "The Chicxulub asteroid impact, combined with ongoing Deccan Traps volcanism in India, disrupted global climate through impact winter, acid rain, and greenhouse warming, causing the end-Cretaceous mass extinction 66 million years ago.": "",
  "How many 'Big Five' mass extinctions have occurred in Earth's history?": "",
  "Three": "",
  "Two": "",
  "Ten": "",
  "Five": "",
  "Earth has experienced five major mass extinction events, each eliminating 75% to 96% of species: the end-Ordovician, Late Devonian, end-Permian, end-Triassic, and end-Cretaceous extinctions.": "",
  "Mammals became dominant after the end-Cretaceous extinction because:": "",
  "They caused the dinosaurs to go extinct through competition": "",
  "The extinction of non-avian dinosaurs opened ecological niches for mammalian diversification": "",
  "They had always been the dominant group on Earth": "",
  "They evolved larger brains that allowed them to survive the asteroid": "",
  "During the Mesozoic, mammals were mostly small, nocturnal creatures overshadowed by dinosaurs, but when the end-Cretaceous extinction eliminated non-avian dinosaurs, mammals rapidly diversified to fill the vacated ecological niches.": "",
