  "Massive volcanic eruptions": "",
  "Glaciation and falling sea levels": "",
  "An asteroid impact": "",
  "A global pandemic among marine organisms": "",
  "A severe glaciation at the end of the Ordovician Period cooled global temperatures dramatically and locked up water in ice sheets, causing sea levels to fall and destroying the shallow marine habitats where most Ordovician life thrived.": "",
  "What evidence supports the asteroid impact theory for the end-Cretaceous extinction?": "",
  "A worldwide layer of iridium-rich clay at the K-Pg boundary, plus the Chicxulub crater in Mexico": "",
  "Written records from ancient civilizations describing the impact": "",
  "A worldwide layer of gold at the K-Pg boundary": "",
  "Fossilized asteroid fragments found inside dinosaur bones": "",
  "The global iridium anomaly (iridium is rare on Earth but common in asteroids), shocked quartz grains, tektites, and the 180-km-wide Chicxulub impact crater in Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula all provide compelling evidence of the asteroid impact.": "",
  "After each mass extinction, surviving species have typically:": "",
  "Diversified rapidly to fill empty ecological niches through adaptive radiation": "",
  "Remained exactly the same for millions of years": "",
  "Stopped evolving completely": "",
  "Slowly died out as well": "",
  "Following mass extinctions, survivors undergo adaptive radiation, rapidly diversifying into many new forms to exploit the ecological niches left vacant by extinct species, often producing entirely new groups of dominant organisms.": "",
