  "The sixth mass extinction, or Anthropocene extinction, refers to the current, human-driven biodiversity crisis in which species are going extinct at 100 to 1,000 times the natural background rate due to habitat destruction, climate change, pollution, and overexploitation.": "",
  "After the end-Permian extinction wiped out 96% of marine species, the fossil record shows that it took approximately 10 million years for marine ecosystems to fully recover. During this recovery, entirely new groups of organisms rose to prominence. What does this pattern reveal about the relationship between mass extinctions and evolution?": "",
  "While mass extinctions cause devastating loss, they also create opportunities for surviving lineages to diversify and evolve into new forms, ultimately driving long-term evolutionary innovation": "",
  "The same species that went extinct eventually reappeared through spontaneous generation": "",
  "Mass extinctions permanently destroy all life and recovery never occurs": "",
  "Recovery always takes exactly 10 million years after every mass extinction": "",
  "Mass extinctions simultaneously destroy existing biodiversity and create evolutionary opportunities by vacating ecological niches, allowing surviving lineages to undergo adaptive radiation and produce entirely new groups of organisms.": "",
  "A marine biologist observes that modern coral reefs are experiencing severe bleaching events due to rising ocean temperatures, and many reef-building coral species are declining rapidly. She notes that reef ecosystems have collapsed multiple times during past mass extinctions and took millions of years to recover. What parallel is she drawing between past and present?": "",
  "Current human-caused warming is stressing reef ecosystems in ways similar to past extinction events, and if coral species are lost, reef recovery could take millions of years": "",
  "Coral reefs have always been indestructible and will survive any environmental change": "",
  "Modern reefs are completely different from ancient reefs and cannot be compared": "",
  "Past reef collapses prove that coral bleaching is completely natural and not a concern": "",
  "The geological record shows that reef-building organisms are highly sensitive to environmental change, and past reef collapses during mass extinctions took millions of years to recover, warning that current human-caused reef destruction could have similarly long-lasting consequences.": "",
  "In 1980, physicist Luis Alvarez and his geologist son Walter proposed that an asteroid impact caused the end-Cretaceous extinction, based on their discovery of an iridium-rich clay layer. Many scientists were initially skeptical. What discovery in 1991 dramatically strengthened their hypothesis?": "",
  "The discovery of dinosaur fossils with iridium in their bones": "",
  "The identification of the buried Chicxulub impact crater on the Yucatan Peninsula, matching the predicted size and age of the impactor": "",
  "The observation of a new asteroid heading toward Earth": "",
  "The discovery that all dinosaurs died at exactly the same moment": "",
  "The identification of the 180-kilometer-wide Chicxulub crater buried beneath the Yucatan Peninsula, dated to precisely 66 million years ago, provided the 'smoking gun' evidence for the Alvarez impact hypothesis by confirming that an asteroid of the predicted size actually struck Earth at the right time.": "",
  "A conservation biologist reports that the current rate of amphibian species extinctions is approximately 45,000 times higher than the background extinction rate. A disease called chytrid fungus is devastating frog populations worldwide, while habitat loss and climate change compound the problem. A student asks whether this qualifies as part of the sixth mass extinction. How should the biologist respond?": "",
  "No, because amphibians are not important enough to count toward a mass extinction": "",
