  "No, because only asteroid impacts can cause mass extinctions": "",
  "No, because mass extinctions only affect marine organisms": "",
  "The catastrophic decline of amphibians worldwide, with extinction rates thousands of times above normal background levels, is one of the most dramatic examples of the proposed sixth mass extinction, demonstrating how multiple human-caused stressors can combine to devastate an entire class of organisms.": "",
  "A paleontologist studying the recovery period after the end-Cretaceous extinction finds that early Cenozoic mammal fossils show a remarkable range of body sizes and ecological roles: tiny insectivores, large herbivores, marine swimmers, and even flying species (bats). During the Mesozoic, most mammals had been small and nocturnal. What evolutionary process explains this dramatic change?": "",
  "Mammals mutated because of radiation from the asteroid impact": "",
  "Mammals were always this diverse but their fossils had not been found yet": "",
  "Adaptive radiation: with dinosaurs gone, mammals diversified rapidly to fill the many vacant ecological niches": "",
  "A sudden climate change made mammals grow larger overnight": "",
  "The explosive diversification of mammals after the dinosaur extinction is a textbook example of adaptive radiation, where a surviving group rapidly evolves into many new forms to exploit ecological niches vacated by the extinct dominant group.": "",
  "Scientists have determined that during the end-Permian extinction, ocean temperatures rose by approximately 10 degrees Celsius, and ocean oxygen levels dropped dramatically. Many marine organisms suffocated. A climate scientist notes similarities to current trends of ocean warming and expanding dead zones. Why is this comparison concerning?": "",
  "Modern marine life is immune to warming and oxygen depletion": "",
