  "The Permian extinction proves that ocean warming is always beneficial for marine life": "",
  "The same mechanisms that caused the worst mass extinction in history, including warming and oxygen depletion, are being replicated today by human-caused climate change, though at a slower rate": "",
  "Current anthropogenic CO2 emissions are causing ocean warming and deoxygenation through the same mechanisms (greenhouse warming, reduced oxygen solubility) that helped drive the end-Permian extinction, raising concerns that continued emissions could trigger similar, devastating marine biodiversity loss.": "",
  "A geology professor explains that after the end-Cretaceous asteroid impact, a global 'impact winter' lasting months to years blocked sunlight, collapsing photosynthesis-based food chains. However, organisms that fed on decaying organic matter (detritivores) and those in deep-ocean food chains survived at higher rates. What does this pattern teach us about mass extinction selectivity?": "",
  "Mass extinctions are selective: organisms whose food chains depended on sunlight-driven photosynthesis were devastated, while those in food chains independent of sunlight had better survival rates": "",
  "All marine organisms survived because the ocean protected them based on established principles": "",
  "Mass extinctions kill all organisms equally, particularly regarding extinction as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Only the largest organisms survived the impact winter, particularly regarding does based on established principles": "",
  "Mass extinctions are not random: the specific kill mechanism determines which organisms survive, and in the case of the impact winter, species dependent on photosynthesis-based food chains were selectively eliminated while detritus-based food chains persisted.": "",
  "A team studying the end-Triassic extinction (201 million years ago) finds evidence of massive volcanic eruptions associated with the breakup of the supercontinent Pangaea. Before the extinction, crocodile-like archosaurs were the dominant land animals. After the extinction, the surviving dinosaurs diversified to fill vacant niches. What does this sequence illustrate about the role of extinction in evolution?": "",
  "Dinosaurs caused the extinction of the archosaurs through competition under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The extinction removed the dominant group (archosaurs), creating the opportunity for dinosaurs to diversify and become dominant through adaptive radiation, showing how extinction reshapes evolutionary trajectories": "",
  "The volcanism directly caused dinosaurs to evolve, particularly regarding supercontinent based on established principles": "",
  "Dinosaurs were always dominant but their early fossils had not been discovered in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The end-Triassic extinction demonstrates how mass extinctions can redirect evolutionary history: by eliminating the dominant archosaurs, the extinction created opportunities for the previously minor dinosaur lineage to undergo adaptive radiation and become the dominant land animals for the next 135 million years.": "",
  "A documentary states that if the Chicxulub asteroid had struck Earth just a few hours earlier or later, it would have hit deep ocean rather than the shallow, sulfur-rich sediments of the Yucatan, potentially producing a much less devastating extinction. A student asks why the impact location mattered. What is the scientific explanation?": "",
