  "A deep-ocean impact would have caused a larger tsunami that killed more organisms following the established framework": "",
  "The impact into sulfur-rich shallow marine sediments vaporized enormous amounts of sulfate and carbonate rock, injecting sulfur aerosols into the atmosphere that intensified the global cooling and acid rain beyond what a deep-ocean impact would have produced": "",
  "The location did not matter; any impact would have produced identical results, particularly regarding devastating under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The Yucatan's sulfur-rich carbonate and evaporite sediments were uniquely destructive because the impact vaporized them, injecting massive amounts of sulfate aerosols into the stratosphere that blocked sunlight and produced sulfuric acid rain, greatly amplifying the extinction beyond the impact alone.": "",
  "A high school class debates whether mass extinctions are ultimately 'good' or 'bad' for the history of life. One group argues they are purely destructive, while another argues they have positive long-term effects. Which statement best represents the scientific understanding?": "",
  "Mass extinctions cause devastating short-term biodiversity loss but drive long-term evolutionary innovation by creating opportunities for surviving lineages to diversify into new forms": "",
  "Mass extinctions have no measurable effect on the overall direction of evolution": "",
  "Mass extinctions are purely beneficial because they make room for better species": "",
  "Mass extinctions are purely destructive with no positive consequences": "",
  "Mass extinctions are double-edged: they cause catastrophic, irreversible loss of species in the short term, but they also fundamentally reshape evolutionary trajectories by removing dominant groups and creating ecological opportunities that drive adaptive radiation and innovation in the long term.": ""
